# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: constitution-of-virginia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The **14th Street bridges** are a set of adjacent five road and rail bridges that cross the Potomac River, connecting Arlington, Virginia and Washington, D.C.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] A major gateway for automotive, bicycle and rail traffic, the bridge complex is named for 14th Street (U.S.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Route 1), which feeds automotive traffic into it on the D.C. end.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The complex contains three four-lane automobile bridges—including, from west to east, one southbound, one bi-directional, and one northbound—that carry Interstate 395 (I-395) and U.S.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Route 1 (US 1) traffic, as well as a bicycle and pedestrian lane on the southbound bridge.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] In addition, the complex contains two rail bridges, one of which carries the Yellow Line of the Washington Metro; the other of which, the only mainline rail crossing of the Potomac River to Virginia, carries a CSX Transportation rail line.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The five bridges, from west to east are the George Mason Memorial Bridge, the Rochambeau Bridge, the Arland D.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] In aerial photos, shadows caused by a large, concrete divider on the bi-directional Rochambeau Bridge create the illusion of two, two-lane bridges, but this is in fact, a single, four-lane structure.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] On January 13, 1982, Air Florida Flight 90 clipped the 14th Street Bridge, the northbound I-395 span of the complex, during rush hour and crashed into the Potomac River; this killed four people on the bridge, along with 74 passengers and crew on the aircraft.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The repaired span was renamed in honor of Arland D.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Williams Jr., a passenger on the plane who survived the initial crash, but drowned after repeatedly passing a helicopter rescue line to other survivors.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Each of the complex's five bridge spans has its own name.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The Metro line connects to a tunnel under Washington Channel that leads into L'Enfant Plaza station.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The mainline railroad from the Long Bridge passes over I-395 before crossing the Washington Channel on a bridge, and then turns northeast along the line of Maryland Avenue.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The name "Long Bridge" was given to a series of bridges across the Potomac dating back to 1809.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] At times, some of the bridges were referred to as the Bridge at 14th Street, but more often by other names.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The first bridge opened as the Washington Bridge on May 20, 1809 and originally carried vehicle, pedestrian and horse traffic.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] By the 1830s it began to be called the "long Bridge across the Potomac" to distinguish it from the bridge near Little Falls, but over time, the colloquial name was shortened to just the "Long Bridge".
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Rails had been built to the bridge from the Washington side in 1855 and from the Virginia side in 1857, but there weren't placed on the bridge until the Civil War.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] In 1864, a new bridge was built adjacent to the original bridge.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Military railroad Charles Minot fell through one of the spans of the old bridge on February 18, 1865, the rails were moved to the new bridge and the old bridge became used for non-rail traffic only, as had been recommended in the prior year.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] To some the old bridge became the "turnpike bridge" and the new one the "railroad bridge." For others the two bridges were referred to separately as the Long Bridge and the railroad bridge or as two parts of one "Long Bridge".
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] An October 1, 1870 flood damaged the bridges beyond repair so a replacement bridge was built over the next two years and the old Washington Bridge was removed.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The day the new bridge opened, the old railroad bridge, which had been partially repaired, was closed.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] On July 2, the Alexandria and Fredericksburg Railway opened, providing the first direct all-rail connection between the north and Richmond, Virginia.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Despite the new design, the 1872 bridge continued to be damaged by freshets, it blocked river traffic and was not wide enough for two tracks; so two new bridges were built.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] A new railroad bridge was constructed in 1904 and a new Highway Bridge opened in December 1906.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The 1872 bridge was closed on December 18, 1906 and demolished in 1907.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] A new swing-span through-truss bridge called the **Highway Bridge** or sometimes the 14th Street Bridge, 500 feet (150 m) upriver from the Long Bridge, opened December 15, 1906, to serve streetcars and other non-railroad traffic.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The yellow trolleys of the Mount Vernon Railway used the bridge until 1932 when the line was replaced by buses that eventually became part of the Alexandria, Barcroft and Washington (AB&W) Transit Company.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] After the George Mason Bridge was opened in 1962, the Highway Bridge was closed, but there was considerable discussion of reusing the Highway Bridge, perhaps for rush hour only automobile traffic.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Nonetheless, the Highway Bridge was finally removed from the site in 1967–1968, and was taken to the Naval Surface Warfare Center, Dahlgren Division, for bombing practice.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] In order to remove the Highway Bridge piers and install new Center Bridge piers, the draw spans of the Williams and Long Bridges were opened for barge and crane equipment in 1967.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] A few years prior to 1967, the railroad bridge had been welded shut, and in order to open it for the crane, that had to be reversed.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The draw spans were opened for the last time on March 3, 1969, when the equipment was removed.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] On July 1, 1942, after two months of work, the War Department opened a pontoon bridge located between the Railroad and Highway bridges.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] It connected Ohio Drive, then Riverside Drive, to US Highway 1.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The bridge was constructed of 30 plank covered pontoons with an asphalt coating for the 12 foot-wide floor.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] A fixed steel span on the Virginia side provided an opening 30 feet wide and 21 feet high for boats to pass under.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Two more fixed spans carried it over the George Washington Parkway.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The bridge was built for emergency movement of troops and though it was to allow for civilian use, it never did.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Once World War II was over, the bridge was removed in the summer of 1945.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Despite the different names of the Rochambeau, Mason and Williams bridges, and the fact that they were all built separately, the three are often called "The 14th Street Bridge" together.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The current railroad bridge opened on August 28, 1904, about 150 feet (45 m) upriver from the old bridge.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] In the early years, the bridge was often referred to as the "Railroad Bridge" to distinguish it from "Highway Bridge".
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] It was also sometimes known as the "14th Street Railroad Bridge".
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] It wasn't until the 1980s, during planning of the Virginia Railway Express (VRE) system, that the railroad bridge again began to be called by the old **"Long Bridge"** name.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The bridge was substantially reconstructed starting in mid-1942, with 11 new supplemental piers between the original truss spans and steel plate girders replacing the iron and steel truss spans.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] When the Mason Bridge was completed in 1962, it put an end to almost all use of the Long Bridge's draw span.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The last time it was opened was March 1969 to allow barges used in the removal of the old Highway Bridge to pass through.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The tender's control house, or shanty, on top of the draw remained - often used as a billboard for Georgetown crew races until it was removed in late 1982 or early 1983.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The bridge was rehabilitated in 2016 and CSX determined that it was sufficient to meet their freight needs, but in 2019 DDOT and FRA reported that a second bridge was needed to serve increased passenger rail needs.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] A third bridge was also proposed to create a new bicycle/pedestrian crossing.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] In 2019, Virginia announced that they would pay to build a new rail bridge over the Potomac River north of the Long Bridge.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Planning for a replacement of the Highway Bridge started in the 1940s to deal with expanded traffic in the automobile age.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Work on a new single-span, northbound-only **14th Street Bridge** began on August 21, 1947, and the new bridge opened on May 9, 1950, with the ribbon cut by Miss D.C., Mary Jane Hayes.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The Highway Bridge then became southbound-only, but a 2nd bridge was planned to replace it.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The new bridge span incorporated draw spans with a control houses that was designed to complement those on the Arlington Memorial Bridge upstream and on the railroad bridge's swing span downstream.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] In 1956, while planning the Jones Point Bridge Congress began to debate what to name it.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] While one of the first suggestions was to name it after Woodrow Wilson, which eventually it was, Rep.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Joel Broyhill (R-VA) suggested naming it for George Mason, or failing that naming the new Highway Bridge for him.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] This prompted a letter to the editor of the Washington Post suggested it be named for revolutionary war hero Lafayette, since it was near where he led soldiers across the river on the way to Yorktown.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] A few days later, Charles Parmer a Rochambeau enthusiast and head of Virginia's short-lived Rochambeau Commission, suggested the bridge instead be named for Jean-Baptiste Donatien de Vimeur, comte de Rochambeau.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Another letter followed that suggested attaching the name Rochambeau instead to the 14th Street Bridge and that letter caught the attention of Congress member Harry F.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Byrd of Virginia who submitted it to the Congressional Record.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Broyhill submitted a bill naming the bridge for Mason and Byrd submitted one naming it for Rochambeau, and by the middle of summer a compromise had been worked out naming one span for each.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Broyhill resubmitted the compromise bill in 1957 and it passed.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The new bridge was dedicated as the **Rochambeau Bridge** on October 19, 1958, at 2 p.m., at time and date meant to correspond with the time and date that Cornwallis surrendered at Yorktown in 1781.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The last time this bridge was opened was on March 3, 1969, to remove barge and crane equipment that had been floated upriver in 1967 to remove the old Highway Bridge piers and install new center bridge piers.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The bridge underwent extensive repair in 1975–1976 which resulted in a closure of more than a year.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Workers gave the bridge a new deck, removed the bascule draw span and replaced the sidewalks with shoulders.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] On January 13, 1982, the bridge was damaged by the crash of Air Florida Flight 90.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The Boeing 737-222, which had accumulated ice while idling on the runway at National Airport, stalled soon after takeoff, fell on the bridge, and slammed into the iced-over Potomac River.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The crash killed 74 passengers and crew, plus four people in cars on the bridge.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The repaired span was renamed the **Arland D.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Memorial Bridge** on March 13, 1985—following a December 4, 1984 vote—after one of the passengers, who passed a lifeline to five survivors before permitting himself to be rescued.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] He succumbed to hypothermia and drowned while first responders worked to rescue the last of the survivors.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The name Rochambeau Bridge was then shifted to the Center Highway Bridge.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] After a series of inspections from 2005 to 2009, the District of Columbia's District Department of Transportation (DDOT) began a $27 million rehabilitation of the northbound main span in 2010.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Construction, scheduled to last only a few months, was finally completed in 2011.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Citing the expense and the need to replace or repair several deficient bridges elsewhere in the District, DDOT pushed the date for fixing these problems to 2020.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] On April 13, 2023, DDOT announced the US Department of Transportation had provided $72 million to help fund the rehabilitation project.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The $90 million project, which will also be funded in part by the D.C. government, would start with preliminary engineering and the environmental review for the project later that spring, with the preliminary design expected to be completed that fall.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Construction is estimated to take two years.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The new **George Mason Memorial Bridge** opened upstream on January 26, 1962, replacing the old Highway Bridge (then southbound only).
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The Mason Bridge, unlike the bridges upstream and downstream, could not open for river traffic, thus Potomac River traffic by sea-going vessels traveling above the Long Bridge ceased in 1961.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] During the late 1960s, new ramps were constructed between the westbound Shirley Highway and the southbound George Washington Parkway and these eliminated the path between the bridge and the Pentagon.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] In 1969, the path was connected to the Arlington Memorial Bridge via the Lady Bird Trail and on April 15, 1972 it was connected to Alexandria via the Mount Vernon Trail, of which the Lady Bird Trail became part.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] In 1984, the Mason Bridge was closed for several months for a $5.9 million overhaul.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The bridge was resurfaced and widened to provide shoulders.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The sidewalk was widened and new safety railings were installed between the walkway and the roadway.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] On July 25, 1989, the George Mason Bridge gained national notoriety as the scene of the 1989 DC Prostitute Expulsion.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] In late 2018, the National Park Service rebuilt and improved the trail ramp between the George Mason Bridge path and East Basin Drive.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] On April 5, 1971, a third bridge opened immediately downstream of the Mason Bridge, carrying two express lanes in each direction.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Work began in March 1967, but wasn't entirely completed until 1972.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The express lanes lead directly to the high-occupancy vehicle lanes on Virginia's section of I-395, though these lanes are only HOV during rush hour.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] When it opened, the bridge was known as the **Center Highway Bridge**.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] At the time it opened it was only open for bus traffic, making it the longest exclusive busway in the country, but over the years the express lane rules have gradually been reduced.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] In late 1973, carpoolers were allowed to use the bus lanes during rush hour if the car had at least four passengers.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] In 1975, cars with four passengers were allowed to use the express lanes at all hours.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] In 1983, Congress passed a law to open the express lanes to all vehicles except during rush hour, when they were restricted to buses, car pools and emergency vehicles and that went into effect in 1985.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] In 1987, due to increased congestion, the Virginia Department of Transportation extended the HOV end time from 6 p.m. to 6:30 p.m., but later that year it was rolled back after Rep.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Stan Parris passed a federal law that would deny Virginia $2.4 million if the rush hour extension remained.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] In the same year, the VDOT opened the northbound HOV lanes on the bridge to all users to alleviate congestion caused by reconstruction of the SE-SW Freeway.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] In early 1989, Virginia, in a deal with Rep.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Parris, lowered the HOV restrictions from four people per vehicle to three in order to regain control over the management of the HOV lanes.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] In late 2019, the HOV lanes on 395 changed to High-Occupancy Toll (HOT) lanes, and as a result the northbound lane on the Rochambeau Bridge became a HOT lane as well.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] On March 13, 1985, following the 1982 Air Florida Flight 90 crash, the downstream bridge was renamed the Arland D.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Memorial Bridge to honor one of the passengers who died saving the lives of other survivors during the crash.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] The name **Rochambeau Bridge** was simultaneously transferred to the Center Highway Bridge.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] However, the bronze marker naming the bridge was not shifted with the name.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Fenwick Bridge**, carrying the Yellow Line, opened on April 30, 1983.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Based on the recommendation of Washington Post reporter Jack Eisen, the bridge was named for Fenwick by the Metro Board on September 22, 1983.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/14th-street-bridges] Fenwick was a Virginia state legislator from the Washington suburbs who sponsored legislation to create Metro.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The first election for Virginia's 5th congressional district took place on February 2, 1789, for a two-year term to commence on March 4 of that year.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In a race that turned on the candidates' positions on the need for amendments (the Bill of Rights) to the recently ratified U.S.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Constitution, James Madison defeated James Monroe for a place in the House of Representatives of the First Congress.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] It is the only congressional election in U.S. history in which two future presidents opposed each other.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] They put forward Monroe, a young but experienced politician who was a war hero wounded at the 1776 Battle of Trenton, as a candidate for the seat.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe did not seek the contest, but once drafted campaigned vigorously.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Despite bitterly cold weather, the two candidates debated outdoors; traveling after one such meeting, Madison suffered frostbite on his face.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Although Madison had earlier stated that amendments to the Constitution were not necessary, during the campaign he took the position that they were, but should be proposed by Congress, rather than by an Article V Convention that Anti-Federalists such as Monroe and Henry supported.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison won the election comfortably, to the satisfaction of his supporters such as President-elect George Washington.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The race did not affect Madison's friendship with Monroe, who was elected to the Senate in 1790, and who would serve as Madison's Secretary of State and succeed him as president in 1817.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] James Madison was born on March 16, 1751 (March 5, 1750, Old Style), at the Belle Grove plantation near Port Conway, Virginia.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He grew up on his parents' estate of Montpelier, and was involved in politics from a young age, serving on the local Committee of Safety at age 23.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He represented Orange County in the Fifth Virginia Convention of 1776.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] After service on the Virginia Council of State, where he forged a lifelong friendship with Governor Thomas Jefferson, he was elected to the Second Continental Congress becoming its youngest member.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He was one of Virginia's delegates to the Constitutional Convention in 1787, and helped persuade General George Washington to be its chair, which gave the convention the moral authority to propose a new plan of government.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He was the originator of the Virginia Plan that became the basis of the federal government proposed by the convention.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] James Monroe was born April 28, 1758, in Westmoreland County, Virginia, the son of prosperous planters, Spence Monroe and Elizabeth Jones Monroe.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] By 1774, the year he entered the College of William & Mary, both his parents had died.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In early 1776, he joined the Virginia militia and became an officer in the Continental Army, later that year being severely wounded at the Battle of Trenton.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He left Continental service in 1779, and was made a colonel in the state militia.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] After the war, Monroe studied law under Jefferson and was elected to the House of Delegates in 1782, and to the Congress of the Confederation in New York in 1783, where he sought to expand the powers of that body.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In 1784, Madison was told by Jefferson that Monroe wanted to begin a correspondence with him, beginning a relationship that would last until Monroe's death in 1831.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The two men differed over whether their state should ratify the Constitution at the Virginia Ratifying Convention, with Madison in favor and Monroe against.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Opponents deemed the proposed national government to be too powerful, and many wanted a second constitutional convention in order to place limits on it.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Despite their efforts, Virginia narrowly ratified the Constitution on June 25, 1788.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe, like Jefferson, believed that there needed to be a Bill of Rights protecting fundamental liberties from infringement by the new federal government.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Ratification had not been a major issue in the Virginia legislative elections of 1788, since it was expected to be decided by the Ratifying Convention that had just been chosen by the voters.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] When the General Assembly convened in October 1788, though, it had a majority of Anti-Federalist members, and was led by Henry, a member of the House of Delegates for Prince Edward County.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry sought to avenge the Anti-Federalist defeat at the Ratifying Convention, and also believed Madison would not seek amendments, or would do so in a lukewarm fashion.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On October 31, the General Assembly re-elected Madison to his seat in the lame-duck Confederation Congress, a body that would cease to exist with the coming of the new federal government.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry's motives in allowing this are uncertain, with some historians stating it was to keep Madison in New York, far from the elections for Congress taking place in Virginia.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Historian Chris DeRose hypothesizes that Madison's seat there was his if he wanted it, and his acceptance meant that he expected to remain in New York (where the new Congress would convene) and win his seat in Virginia without needing to campaign.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison, who sought election to the House of Representatives, yielded to Washington and the Federalist minority in the legislature and allowed his name to be put forward in the legislature's election for Virginia's two U.S. senators—until 1913, senators were elected by the state legislatures.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry nominated two Anti-Federalists, Richard Henry Lee and William Grayson, while Madison was the sole Federalist named.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry told the General Assembly that Madison was "unworthy of the confidence of the people" and that his election "would terminate in producing rivulets of blood throughout the land".
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry's nominees were elected, Lee with 98 votes and Grayson with 86, while the defeated Madison gained 77.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The General Assembly turned its attention to dividing the state into congressional districts.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's home county, Orange, was placed in a district with seven others, five of which had elected representatives to the Ratifying Convention who had opposed ratification, while Orange and one other had voted in favor and one county's delegation had split its vote.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The General Assembly required that candidates live in the district, a qualification not found in the federal Constitution.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Fauquier County, closely associated with Orange both geographically and economically, had supported ratification, but was excluded despite the efforts of Federalists.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Despite some stating that Henry had contrived a district in which Madison was sure to be defeated, Thomas Rogers Hunter in a journal article examined the question, and concluded, "the district was compact and bounded on all sides by natural geographic features.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Simply put, Patrick Henry did not attempt to gerrymander James Madison out of a seat in the first U.S.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Congress." Virginia's 5th congressional district consisted of the counties of Albemarle, Amherst, Culpeper, Fluvanna, Goochland, Louisa, Orange and Spotsylvania.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Some of these counties were later divided, so the district that Madison contested also included the present-day counties of Greene, Madison, Nelson and Rappahannock.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] French Strother, a long-time Virginia legislator from Culpeper County who had opposed ratification at the Virginia Convention, was solicited as a candidate to oppose Madison, but declined.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] William Cabell, of Amherst County, was also considered as an Anti-Federalist candidate but Monroe was selected instead.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Both Strother and Cabell threw their support behind Monroe.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] A resident of Spotsylvania County, Monroe was reluctant to run against his friend Madison, but was probably encouraged by Henry, George Mason and other Anti-Federalists, though discouraged by his uncle, Joseph Jones.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] His service in the Revolutionary War, and his political service after it, were electoral assets.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The selection of Monroe was enough to worry Washington: "Sorry indeed should I be if Mr.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Federalist Henry Lee wrote to him, "I profess myself pleased with your exclusion from the senate & I wish it may so happen in the lower house [in which case] you will be left qualified to take part in the administration, which is the place proper for you".
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Nevertheless, Henry Lee believed Madison would win, calling Monroe "the beau".
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison disliked electioneering, but realized he would have to campaign hard to win the race.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The Fifth District race would be the only congressional election in history to oppose two future U.S. presidents.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The largest issue in the campaign was the question of a Bill of Rights protecting personal freedoms as amendments to the Constitution.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's view had been that these were unnecessary as the Federal government had only limited power and that in any event, the new government should be allowed to operate for a time before changes were made to the Constitution.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] To take such a stance in the campaign would be political suicide, and Madison recognized that there was widespread support for such amendments.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] But he felt it to be important that Congress proposed them, believing that route to be a quicker, easier, and safer means of passage than an Article V convention, which was favored by the Anti-Federalists such as Monroe.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Nevertheless, he was skeptical about the effect of such amendments, calling them "parchment barriers", ineffective if the Federal government was determined to bypass them.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He told the voters that if elected, he would work diligently for the passage of a Bill of Rights.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's earlier stances made it easy to depict him in this light.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's pledge to support a Bill of Rights if elected left the question of direct taxation as the major difference between them.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe believed the power of the Federal government to directly tax the citizens to be not only unnecessary, but injurious to American liberty.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He felt the government could raise money by tariffs, by the sale of public lands, or by borrowing.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison responded that were the Federal government unable to tax citizens directly, tariffs would be the major source of revenue, and this would disproportionately hurt the South, which had few manufactures and imported heavily from overseas.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He also stated that having federal taxes paid in each state would help bind the nation together as giving each a financial stake in the Union's success.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison had been in New York, helping to wrap up the affairs of the old Congress of the Confederation.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He received letters from other parts of Virginia from those who believed the residency requirement unconstitutional, offering to have him run there, but he preferred to run in his home district, and he declined.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] A trip to Virginia on horseback or in a carriage would be personally hard on Madison, then suffering from a bad case of hemorrhoids.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On December 8, 1788, he wrote to Jefferson (who was in Paris) that he would return to Virginia to campaign for his election, a decision prompted in part by warnings from Virginians that he could not win without personally fighting for the seat.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He arrived at Washington's plantation, Mount Vernon, on December 18, for a visit that lasted until he returned home to Orange County and his estate, Montpelier, just after Christmas.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] From the time Madison arrived in Virginia, the weather was unusually cold and snowy; the candidates often had to speak in freezing conditions, and the last weekend before the election saw 10 inches (250 mm) of snow.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Aware he was not an orator of Henry's quality, Madison launched a letter-writing campaign, advocating for the new Constitution; though initially taken by surprise, Monroe also set out his positions in letters.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] It was Madison's intent, in writing to key citizens in each community, both to enlist support, and have the recipients circulate the letters locally or publish them in local newspapers.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] For Monroe's part, according to DeRose, he "poured himself into the campaign with frenetic energy, determined to campaign everywhere, to personally engage voters, and to make liberal use of his pen to correspond with community leaders.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Considering him as being able to render his Country Great Services on this important occasion".
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On January 7, 1789, Virginians chose electors who would vote for the first U.S. president.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The districts for this were not coextensive with congressional districts, since Virginia was entitled to 12 electors but only 10 congressmen.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Still, six of the counties in the Fifth District were in the same district for choosing an elector, and the race featured a Federalist and Anti-Federalist, though both were pledged to vote for Washington for president.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Goochland and Louisa counties were not in that electoral district, but Buckingham County was.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The Federalist, Edward Stevens, was elected, and outpolled his opponent within the Fifth District, but both parties took hope from the result, with the Anti-Federalists cheered by the fact that Stevens had easily taken Spotsylvania County, where the local favorite Monroe would presumably do better.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The candidates sought to appeal to the local religious communities, of which the Baptists were the most influential.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] That community had taken the position that the Constitution did not provide sufficient protection for their religious liberty.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's pledge of support for amendments defused much of the Anti-Federalist anger against him.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The two men were quite friendly with each other, and decided to travel together between debates, riding from courthouse to courthouse, making speeches before large crowds.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] These debates showed the physical contrast between the tall, athletic Monroe, who had a full head of brown hair, and the short, slender Madison and his receding hairline.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] They often rode together, ate together, and lodged in the same room.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In 18th century Virginia, Court Day, a different day in each local county, was not only an opportunity for lawyers and judges to try cases, but a social gathering, including fairs, markets, and other events.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The candidates addressed those present, sometimes speaking for hours to the largest crowds they were likely to find during the campaign.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry Lee wrote to Washington three days later, "Mr Madison is gaining ground fast but still he is involved in much doubt & difficulty.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The debate that DeRose deemed perhaps the most significant of the race took place one evening at the Hebron Lutheran Church in Culpeper (today in Madison County).
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The Lutherans, like the Baptists, had been persecuted in America, and generally voted as a bloc to maximize their influence.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe and Madison attended the worship service, after which there was musical entertainment featuring fiddles.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] They and the congregation then went outside, and the two candidates debated on the front porch as the congregation stood in the bitter cold, with snow on the ground, likely for hours.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Riding away afterwards, likely home to Montpelier, Madison suffered a frostbitten nose.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In his old age, former president Madison would tell the story of that night, and point to the left side of his nose, saying he had battle scars.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] White males who were 21 years of age or older and who owned 50 acres (20 ha) of unimproved land or half that with a house were eligible to vote in the Fifth District.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Approximately 5,189 voters formed the district's electorate.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Per the 1790 census, there were 11,231 free white males age over 16 in the district, so about half of free white men were able to vote.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The total population (including women, slaves and children) of the district was 91,007, so the electorate made up less than 6% of the total population, and perhaps 12–15% of those aged over 21.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] There was no secret ballot in Virginia elections in 1789; voters entered the local courthouse and publicly declared their votes, to be recorded by a clerk.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The elections were administered by county sheriffs, normally the senior justice of the peace who had not already served in that capacity.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Due to the bitterly cold weather in the Fifth District, the sheriffs in some counties extended voting beyond February 2, allowing more voters to reach their county courthouse.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] This was not authorized by Virginia law, but had also occurred in the voting for presidential electors the previous month.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] To get out the vote, Madison's supporters sent wagons around to transport voters to the polls.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] They brought one very old man from a distance, and he listened to them talk and asked if the Monroe spoken of was the son of Spence Monroe, formerly of Westmoreland County.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On being told he was, the man declared he would vote for James Monroe, for "I do not know James Madison", but Spence Monroe had once fed him, clothed him and sheltered him.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Once the polls closed, the local sheriff went to the door of the courthouse and proclaimed the result.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] It took time for complete results to be compiled; partial returns were printed in newspapers.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On February 10, the sheriffs of the eight counties of the Fifth District met at Albemarle's courthouse, as the county first named in the election statute, to certify the results.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Their returns indicated that Madison won the election with 1,308 votes to 972 for Monroe.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In Madison's home county of Orange, he received 216 votes to Monroe's 9, in Culpeper 256 to Monroe's 103; he won Albemarle County by 69 votes and Louisa by 104.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison had given considerable attention to Orange, apparently spending the day of the polls there despite the urgings of some supporters to base himself for the day in a more populous county, and two-thirds of his margin of victory came from Orange.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Strong Baptist support for Madison there contributed to the outcome.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison had been able to hold down the margin in strongly Anti-Federalist Amherst to 246–145 for Monroe, who also took his home county of Spotsylvania by 74 votes, Fluvanna by 21 and Goochland by 1 vote.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The Baptists favored Madison due to his record of support for religious liberty.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] After the election, Madison wrote to Jefferson, "It was my misfortune to be thrown into a contest with our friend, Col.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The occasion produced considerable efforts among our respective friends.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] According to Stewart, "Barely thirty years old, Monroe had time to make his way.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In the House of Representatives, Madison introduced and guided to passage the amendments that became known as the Bill of Rights.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He broke with Washington over the administration's policies, and allied with Jefferson, helping gain the latter's election to the presidency, and became his Secretary of State in 1801.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He succeeded Jefferson as president in 1809.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Although defeated for Congress, Monroe's frequent court appearances as a lawyer kept him in the public eye in Virginia.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In 1790, after Grayson's death, the General Assembly elected him to the U.S.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He served thereafter in a number of offices, including, twice, Governor of Virginia, and in 1811 Madison named Monroe as Secretary of State.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe was elected president in succession to Madison in 1816, taking office the following year.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1790–91 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 27, 1790, and October 11, 1791.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before or after the first session of the 2nd United States Congress convened on October 24, 1791.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was the first midterm election cycle, which took place in the middle of President George Washington's first term.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The size of the House increased to 67 seats after the new state of Vermont elected its first representatives.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] While formal political parties still did not exist, coalitions of pro-Washington (Pro-Admin.) representatives and anti-Administration representatives each gained two seats as a result of the addition of new states to the union.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Speaker Frederick Muhlenberg was succeeded by Jonathan Trumbull Jr., who became the 2nd Speaker of the House.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Either five or six incumbents did not seek re-election.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Aedanus Burke, a U.S. representative from South Carolina's 2nd congressional district, either retired or lost re-election but it is not known.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania at-large: Henry Wynkoop retired.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania at-large: Thomas Scott retired.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In this period, each state fixed its own date for congressional general elections, as early as April 27, 1790 (in New York) and as late as October 11, 1791 (in Pennsylvania).
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections to a Congress took place both in the even-numbered year before and in the odd-numbered year when the Congress convened.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year).
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first session of this Congress was convened in Philadelphia on October 24, 1791.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Kentucky and Vermont became states during the 2nd Congress, adding two seats each.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The legislation admitted Vermont was passed at the end of the 1st Congress taking effect on March 4, 1791, the first day of the 2nd Congress, so that Vermont was represented from the start of the Congress, while Kentucky was unrepresented until the 2nd session.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special elections in 1790 and 1791 during the 1st United States Congress and 2nd United States Congress.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New states and newly ratified states are not included as special elections.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections are sorted by date then district.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Connecticut elected all five of its representatives at-large on a general ticket on September 20, 1790.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were two subsequent special elections.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first was held to fill the vacancy left by Pierpont Edwards (Pro-Admin.) declining to serve and was won by Jeremiah Wadsworth (Pro-Admin.).
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The second was held September 19, 1791, to fill the vacancy left by Roger Sherman (Pro-Admin.)'s election to the Senate and was won by Amasa Learned (Pro-Admin.).
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Georgia switched to a conventional district system for the Second Congress.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] At the time, the districts were not numbered, but are retroactively renumbered as the 1st, 2nd, and 3rd respectively here.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Kentucky was admitted during the 2nd Congress and elected its first representatives in 1792.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In Maryland, two local factions briefly emerged, the Chesapeake and Potomac (or Potowmack) "parties".
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The Potomac faction, consisting of individuals from the small counties of southern Maryland and the Eastern Shore, aimed to maintain their status by curbing the increasing influence of the city of Baltimore and the more populous counties.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] To do so, they supported the development of the federal city and a canal on the Potomac River to secure their economic future.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Conversely, the Chesapeake faction advocated for Baltimore's growth.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Their strategy involved improving the Susquehanna River to channel the lucrative wheat trade from western Maryland and Pennsylvania through Baltimore.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They also believed that political representation should reflect population growth patterns rather than be defined by the counties.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They feared that a canal on the Potomac River would undermine Baltimore's prosperity by diverting trade to competitors like Georgetown, the proposed federal city, and Alexandria.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Temporarily setting aside differences at the national level, the "Chesapeake Ticket" was formed to punish incumbents who had supported the Potomac location for the proposed federal city.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] A "Potomac Ticket" was organized and led by Governor Smallwood.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Turnout in Baltimore was around 99%, and almost every ballot was cast for the Chesapeake Ticket.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Statewide, the ticket won an overwhelming majority, securing all six seats.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This victory threatened the county-based rural oligarchy, prompting the House of Delegates to transition from a mixed system to a district-based system on December 19, 1790.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Under this new system, all of Baltimore's votes would go to just one representative, Harford County was grouped with Kent and Cecil Counties, and Anne Arundel County was grouped with Prince George's County and Annapolis.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the base of the Chesapeake "party" split between three districts, the Chesapeake faction would disappear.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts law required a majority for election.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This condition was met in four of the eight districts, the remaining four required between 2 and 9 ballots for election.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New York's districts were not numbered at the time, therefore the numbering here is retroactive.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina ratified the Constitution November 21, 1789, and elected its representatives after admission.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to the cession of North Carolina's trans-Appalachian territory to form the Southwest Territory, the territory of the old 5th district was lost.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina retained the same number of Representatives, and so it redistricted for the Second Congress.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania had elected its Representatives at-large in the 1st Congress, but switched to using districts in the 2nd Congress.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Five incumbents ran for re-election, four of whom won, while three others retired leaving three open seats.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Two districts had no incumbents residing in them, while one (the 8th district) had a single representative who declined to run for re-election and one (the 2nd district) had three incumbents, only one of whom ran for re-election.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution May 29, 1790.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] It elected its representatives after admission.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island held elections for the 2nd Congress on October 18, 1790, about six weeks after elections for the 1st Congress due to the state's late ratification of the Constitution.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont was admitted at the end of the First Congress, with the admission taking effect at the start of the Second Congress.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont was entitled to elect two representatives.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont law at the time required a majority to win an office.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the 1st district, no candidate won a majority, necessitating a run-off.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1792–93 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between August 27, 1792, and September 6, 1793.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 3rd United States Congress convened on December 2, 1793.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the addition of the new state of Kentucky's representatives, and the congressional reapportionment based on the 1790 United States census, the size of the House increased to 105 seats.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They coincided with the re-election of President George Washington.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] While Washington ran for president as an independent, his followers (more specifically, the supporters of Alexander Hamilton) formed the nation's first organized political party, the Federalist Party, whose members and sympathizers are identified as pro-Administration on this page.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In response, followers of Thomas Jefferson and James Madison created the opposition Democratic-Republican Party, who are identified as anti-Administration on this page.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The Federalists promoted urbanization, industrialization, mercantilism, a centralized government, and a broad interpretation of the United States Constitution.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In contrast, the Democratic-Republicans supported the ideal of an agrarian republic made up of self-sufficient farmers and small, localized governments with limited power.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Despite nearly unanimous support for Washington as a presidential candidate, Jeffersonian ideas edged out Hamiltonian principles at the ballot box for congressional candidates, with the Democratic-Republicans taking 24 seats more than they had prior to the organization of their political movement.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Most of the increase was due to the addition of new seats in Western regions as a result of the 1790 census.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Dominated by agrarian culture, these Western territories offered strong support to Democratic-Republican congressional candidates.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] As a result, they secured a thin majority in the legislature.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In this period, each state fixed its own date for its congressional election as early as August 1792 (in New Hampshire and Rhode Island) and as late as September 1793 (in Kentucky).
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year), but as the first session of Congress typically began in November or December, the elections took place before Congress actually met.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The 3rd Congress first met on December 2, 1793.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] These were the first elections held after reapportionment following the first census.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Thirty-six new seats were added, with 1 state losing 1 seat, 3 states having no change, and the remaining 11 states gaining between 1 and 9 seats.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was the first apportionment based on actual census data, the apportionment for the 1st and 2nd Congresses being set by the Constitution using estimated populations.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With new seats, due to reapportionment, outlined.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special elections in 1792 and 1793 during the 2nd and 3rd United States Congresses.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections are sorted here by state then district.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Connecticut gained two seats in reapportionment following the 1790 census.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Three special elections followed the 1792 elections in Connecticut after Representatives-elect Sturges and Huntington resigned before the start of Congress and Mitchell was elected to the Senate.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Delaware's apportionment did not change following the 1790 census.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] As in the 1st and 2nd Congresses, each voter cast votes for two separate candidates, at least one of whom had to be from a different county as the voter.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Following the 1790 census, Georgia's apportionment was decreased from 3 seats to 2 (the only state whose representation decreased after the census).
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Georgia switched from separate districts to at-large seats.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Maryland increased from 6 to 8 representatives after the 1790 census.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The previous mixed district/at-large system was replaced with a conventional district system.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Following the 1790 census, Massachusetts's representation increased from eight to fourteen Representatives and was redistricted into four plural districts, plus a single at-large district.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The 4th district covered the District of Maine (the modern-day State of Maine).
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The plural districts were concurrent tickets rather than a single general ticket, though the 1st and 2nd districts appeared to have also had a general ticket alongside the more specific tickets.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] As before, a majority was required for election, in those districts where a majority was not achieved, additional ballots were required.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New Hampshire increased from 3 seats to 4 seats after the 1790 census.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Following the 1790 census, New Jersey's apportionment increased from 4 to 5 seats.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to re-apportionment following the 1790 census, New York's congressional delegation grew from 6 to 10.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Three incumbents ran for re-election, two of whom won, and the other three incumbents retired.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the increase following re-apportionment, this left seven open seats.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Following the 1790 census, North Carolina's apportionment increased from 5 to 10 seats.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania switched from using districts to electing its representatives on an at-large basis for the 3rd Congress, just as it had done for the 1st Congress.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This would be the last time that Pennsylvania would elect all of its Representatives at-large.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to re-apportionment following the 1790 census, Pennsylvania's delegation increased from 8 representatives to 13.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island gained a second representative from the results of the 1790 census.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island did not divide itself into districts, but elected two at-large representatives.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] South Carolina gained one representative as a result of the 1790 census, increasing from 5 to 6.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont had no apportionment in the House of Representatives before 1790 census because it was not admitted to the Union until 1791.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont's election laws at the time required a majority to win election to the House of Representatives.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] If no candidate won a majority, a runoff election was held, which happened in the 1st district.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Virginia gained nine representatives from the 1790 census, and in addition, the old 2nd district was lost after its territory became the new State of Kentucky.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were, therefore, ten new districts created for the 3rd Congress.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1794-and-1795-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1794–95 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between August 25, 1794 (New Hampshire), and September 5, 1795 (Kentucky).
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1794-and-1795-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 4th United States Congress convened on December 7, 1795.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1794-and-1795-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They were held during President George Washington's second term.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1794-and-1795-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections were held for all 105 seats, representing 15 states.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1794-and-1795-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the first election for the House of Representatives with organized political parties, the Democratic-Republican Party, which opposed the incumbent Washington Administration, defeated the pro-administration Federalist Party.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1794-and-1795-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The outgoing speaker, Frederick Muhlenberg, had supported the pro-administration forces during his first two terms, but was elected by a coalition made up mainly of anti-administration members in 1793, and by 1795 he was seen as more favorable to the Democratic-Republicans.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1794-and-1795-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Despite the Democratic-Republican majority, however, Muhlenberg was not re-elected, and was succeeded by Federalist Jonathan Dayton.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1794-and-1795-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] During this period, each state fixed its own date for a congressional general election.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1794-and-1795-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections took place both in the even-numbered year before and in the odd-numbered year when a Congress convened.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1794-and-1795-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special and late elections to the 3rd and 4th Congresses in 1794 and 1795.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1794-and-1795-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Only two candidates are recorded for Delaware's congressional election in 1794, suggesting that the voting procedure in place for the first three Congresses for two candidates had been changed.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1794-and-1795-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts redistricted between the 3rd and 4th Congress, dividing itself into 14 districts.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1794-and-1795-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The 12th-14th districts were in the District of Maine (the modern State of Maine).
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1794-and-1795-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Additional ballots were required in five districts due to the majority requirement not being met on the first ballot.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1794-and-1795-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Under New Hampshire's electoral laws, a majority of voters (12.5% of votes) was required for election.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1794-and-1795-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Only three candidates achieved a majority, and so a run-off election was held for the fourth seat.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1794-and-1795-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New York's districts were not numbered at the time, but were later numbered retroactively.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1794-and-1795-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania once again divided itself into districts instead of electing representatives at-large, as it had for the 3rd Congress.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1794-and-1795-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The state divided intself into 12 districts, one of which (the 4th) had two seats.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1794-and-1795-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania would continue to use one or more plural districts until 1842.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1794-and-1795-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Electoral data are only available for the 1st and 5th district of South Carolina's 6 districts at the time of the elections of 1794.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1794-and-1795-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Representative-elect Barnwell of the 2nd district declined to serve.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1794-and-1795-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] A special election was held to fill the resulting vacancy, electing Wade Hampton (Democratic-Republican).
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1794-and-1795-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont law required a majority for election to Congress, with a second election to be held if the first did not return a majority.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1794-and-1795-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Run-off elections were required in both districts.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 4 to December 7, 1808.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican candidate James Madison defeated Federalist candidate Charles Cotesworth Pinckney decisively.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Madison had served as Secretary of State since President Thomas Jefferson took office in 1801.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson, who had declined to run for a third term, threw his strong support behind Madison, a fellow Virginian.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Sitting Vice President George Clinton and former Ambassador James Monroe both challenged Madison for leadership of the party, but Madison won his party's nomination and Clinton was renominated as vice president.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists chose to re-nominate Pinckney, a former ambassador who had served as the party's 1804 nominee, again alongside Rufus King.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Despite the unpopularity of the Embargo Act of 1807, Madison won the vast majority of electoral votes outside of the Federalist stronghold of New England.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton received six electoral votes for president from his home state of New York.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] This election was the first of two instances in American history in which a new president was selected but the incumbent vice president won re-election, the other being in 1828.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Bradley, who had chaired the congressional nominating caucus during the 1804 presidential election, made a call for the 1808 caucus to the 146 Democratic-Republican members of the United States Congress and Federalist allies.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The caucus was attended by 89 to 94 members of Congress.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] With the support of outgoing President Thomas Jefferson, Secretary of State James Madison won the presidential nomination over opposing candidates James Monroe and Vice President George Clinton.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The caucus voted to give the vice presidential nomination to Clinton over his main opponent John Langdon, although Clinton's supporters believed Clinton would receive the Federalist Party's presidential nomination.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists instead nominated Charles Cotesworth Pinckney that September.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] A committee of fifteen members was selected to manage Madison's campaign.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Seventeen Democratic-Republicans in Congress opposed Madison's selection and the caucus system whose authority to select presidential and vice-presidential candidates was disputed.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Monroe, who was supported by dissident and majority leader John Randolph, was nominated by a group of Virginia Democratic-Republicans (Old Republicans), and although he did not actively try to defeat Madison, he also refused to withdraw from the race.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton was also supported by a group of New York Democratic-Republicans for president even as he remained the party's official vice presidential candidate.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalist caucus met in September 1808 and re-nominated the party's 1804 ticket, which consisted of General Charles Cotesworth Pinckney of South Carolina and former Senator Rufus King of New York.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] This was the only time in American history that a defeated major party renominated its losing ticket for a second time.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The election was marked by opposition to Jefferson's Embargo Act of 1807, a halt to trade with Europe that disproportionately hurt New England merchants and was perceived as favoring France over Britain.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Nonetheless, Jefferson was still very popular with Americans generally and Pinckney was soundly defeated by Madison, though not as badly as in 1804.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney received few electoral votes outside of New England.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney retained the electoral votes of the two states that he carried in 1804 (Connecticut and Delaware), and he also picked up New Hampshire, Massachusetts, Rhode Island, and three electoral districts in North Carolina besides the two electoral districts in Maryland that he carried earlier.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Except for the North Carolina districts, all of the improvement was in New England.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] Monroe won a portion of the popular vote in Virginia and North Carolina, while the New York legislature split its electoral votes between Madison and Clinton.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The popular vote totals used are the elector from each party with the highest total of votes.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1808-united-states-presidential-election] The vote totals of Kentucky, North Carolina, and Tennessee appear to be incomplete.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1810-state-of-the-union-address] The **1810 State of the Union Address** was given during the first term of President James Madison, the fourth president of the United States.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1810-state-of-the-union-address] It was given on Wednesday, December 5, 1810 in Washington, D.C.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1810-state-of-the-union-address] It was "concerning the commercial intercourse between the United States and Great Britain and France and their dependencies having invited in a new form a termination of their edicts against our neutral commerce." It was given to the 11th United States Congress.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1810-state-of-the-union-address] Notably, the President mentioned the overall relations with the Barbary States and Native Americans were improving.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/1810-state-of-the-union-address] The address also contains mention of the state of affairs with Spanish Florida and the President noted that he was in contact with the Spanish Monarchy to discuss land boundaries.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The **Constitution of the Commonwealth of Virginia** is the document that defines and limits the powers of the state government and the basic rights of the citizens of the Commonwealth of Virginia.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Like all other state constitutions, it is supreme over Virginia's laws and acts of government, though it may be superseded by the United States Constitution and U.S. federal law as per the Supremacy Clause.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The original Virginia Constitution of 1776 was enacted at the time of the Declaration of Independence by the first thirteen states of the United States of America.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Virginia was an early state to adopt its own Constitution on June 29, 1776, and the document was widely influential both in the United States and abroad.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] In addition to frequent amendments, there have been six major subsequent revisions of the constitution (by Conventions for the constitutions of 1830, 1851, 1864, 1870, 1902, and by commission for 1971 amendments).
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] These new constitutions have been part of, and in reaction to, periods of major regional or social upheaval in Virginia.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] For instance, the 1902 constitution included provisions to disenfranchise African Americans, who in 1900 made up nearly 36% of the state's population.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] They did not regain suffrage until after the enactment of federal civil rights legislation in the mid-1960s.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The drafting of the first Virginia Constitution began in early 1776, amidst the American colonies' break with Britain.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] George Mason and James Madison played central roles in shaping the document.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Although Thomas Jefferson submitted a draft from the Second Continental Congress in Philadelphia, it arrived too late to be considered.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Madison's involvement in Virginia’s founding charter would later inform his work on the United States Constitution.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Jefferson later criticized the final version, arguing it lacked sufficient structural checks and failed to secure a truly balanced republican government.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Adopted on June 29, 1776, the Constitution formally dissolved Virginia’s allegiance to the British crown and accused King George III of tyranny.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] It created a bicameral legislature—the General Assembly—and established a weak executive branch, with a governor elected annually by the legislature.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The accompanying Virginia Declaration of Rights, drafted by Mason, outlined core political principles, including the inherent rights of individuals and the fundamental purpose of government.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Declaration of Independence and later served as a model for the U.S.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] While revolutionary in tone, the 1776 Constitution preserved many aspects of colonial governance.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Drawing on Enlightenment philosophy—especially John Locke's theories of natural rights—the framers emphasized legislative supremacy and separation of powers, though in practice most authority remained in the General Assembly.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Both the executive and judiciary were appointed by the legislature, creating little institutional independence.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Historian Brent Tarter argues this structure "entrenched the power of the landed gentry" and ensured continued dominance by Virginia’s elite families.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Representation was based on fixed counties rather than population, disproportionately empowering eastern slaveholding regions over growing western settlements.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Suffrage was limited to white male property owners, excluding most Virginians from political participation.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] It was also silent on slavery, leaving the institution legally untouched—an omission that, according to Tarter, signaled tacit approval.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Despite these limitations, the Constitution of 1776 significantly influenced other revolutionary governments.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Wood describes it as a blueprint for state-building, particularly in its emphasis on written rights declarations and legislative dominance, although later generations would criticize the imbalance of power it created.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Legal scholar Stephen McCullough observes that courts have since interpreted the document as coextensive with federal constitutional protections, often neglecting the unique rights and traditions rooted in Virginia's own legal history.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] He argues that “preserving the vitality of the Virginia Constitution depends on active interpretation,” and calls for greater scholarly and judicial engagement with its original meaning.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] By the 1820s, Virginia was one of only two states that limited voting to landowners.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] In addition, because representation was by county rather than population, the residents of increasingly populous Western Virginia (the area that would become West Virginia in 1863) had grown discontented at their limited representation in the legislature.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Pressure increased until a constitutional convention was convened in 1829–1830.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] This convention became largely a contest between eastern Virginia planters of the slaveholding elite and the less affluent yeomen farmers of Western Virginia.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Issues of representation and suffrage dominated the debate.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Delegates to the convention included such prominent Virginians as James Madison, James Monroe, John Tyler, and John Marshall.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Western leaders included Philip Doddridge and Alexander Campbell.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The convention ultimately compromised by loosening suffrage requirements.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] It also reduced the number of senators and delegates to the Virginia General Assembly.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The resulting constitution was ratified by a popular majority, though most of the voters in the western part of the state ended up voting against it.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Thus, the underlying intrastate tensions remained, and would have to be addressed later.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] As of the 1840 census, the majority of the white residents of the state lived in western Virginia, but they were underrepresented in the legislature because of the continued property requirement for voting; not all held sufficient property to vote.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] This compounded their dissatisfaction with the apportionment scheme adopted in 1830, which was based on counties rather than population, thus giving disproportionate power to the fewer, but propertied whites who lived in the eastern part of the state and kept a grip on the legislature.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] As the state legislature also elected the governor and the United States senators, Western Virginians felt they had little influence on state leadership.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Their attempts to win electoral reform in the Virginia legislature were defeated each time.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Some began to openly discuss the abolition of slavery or secession from the state.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Ultimately, the eastern planters could not continue to ignore their discontent, and a new constitutional convention was called to resolve the continuing tensions.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The most significant change adopted in the 1851 Constitution was elimination of the property requirement for voting, resulting in extension of the suffrage to all white males of voting age.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The 1851 Constitution established popular election for the governor, the newly created office of lieutenant governor, and all Virginia judges, rather than the election of the top two state officers by the legislature, or political appointment for judges.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Because of these changes, the 1851 Virginia Constitution became known as the "Reform Constitution".
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] When in 1861, the Virginia legislature voted for secession in the events leading up to the American Civil War, all of the western and several of the northern counties dissented.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] They set up a separate government with Francis H.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] During the Civil War, this separate or "restored" government approved the creation of West Virginia as a separate state (which was admitted to the Union in 1863) and in 1864 it approved a new Constitution.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The constitution was the product of a divided state and government; it was the first since the original 1776 Constitution to be adopted by the legislature without a popular vote.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The 1864 Constitution abolished slavery in Virginia, disenfranchised men who had served in the Confederate government, recognized the creation of the State of West Virginia, and adjusted the number and terms of office of the members of the Virginia Assembly.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The foreword to the current Virginia Constitution does not include the 1864 Constitution in its list of previous constitutions.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] It notes that the 1864 Constitution was drafted under wartime conditions and was of uncertain legal status.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] After the end of the Civil War, Virginia came briefly under military rule during Reconstruction, with the district commanded by John M.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Pursuant to federal Reconstruction legislation, Schofield called for a new constitutional convention to meet in Richmond from December 1867 to April 1868.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] In protest of freedmen's suffrage, many of Virginia's conservative whites refused to participate in voting for delegates.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] As a result, Republicans led by Judge John Curtiss Underwood dominated the convention.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Opponents called the result the "Underwood Constitution" or the "Negro Constitution", as it gave freedmen suffrage.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Controversy over clauses that continued the temporary disenfranchisement of former Confederate government members delayed the adoption of the Constitution.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] An eventual compromise provided for separate voting disenfranchisement clauses and the rest of the Constitution; the former failed to win approval.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The remainder of the Underwood Constitution was ratified by a popular vote of 210,585 to 9,136 and went into effect in 1870.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] In the late nineteenth century, white Democrats regained power in state legislatures across the South.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] They passed Jim Crow laws establishing racial segregation in public facilities and restricting the lives of blacks.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] By the turn of the 20th century, six Southern states had essentially eliminated the black vote, and pressure mounted among whites in Virginia to do the same, ostensibly as a way to stop electoral fraud and corruption.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The 1901 constitutional convention met in this climate.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Members were focused on restricting black voting rights without violating the Fifteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution or disenfranchising poor whites.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Led by the future Senator Carter Glass, the convention created requirements that all prospective voters had to pay poll taxes or pass a literacy test administered by white registrars.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] An exemption was granted, in a kind of grandfather clause, for military veterans and sons of veterans, who were virtually all white.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The changes effectively disenfranchised black voters, though many illiterate whites were also unable to meet the new requirements.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] In 1900 blacks made up nearly 36 percent of the population.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] In succeeding elections, the Virginia electorate was reduced by nearly half as a result of the changes.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] When adjusted for the Nineteenth Amendment, voter turnout would not return to 1900 levels until 1952 within a statewide population almost twice the size.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The small electorate was key to maintaining the dominant Democratic Organization in power for sixty years.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Other significant provisions of the 1902 Constitution imposed racial segregation in public schools (which already existed on a *de facto* basis) and abolished the county court system.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The Constitution provided for the creation of the State Corporation Commission to regulate the growing power of the railroads.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Because of concern over African American opposition, the convention did not honor its pledge to have the proposed constitution put to popular vote.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Like the 1864 Constitution by the Loyalist government during the Civil War, the legislature adopted the 1902 Constitution without ratification by the electorate.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] It was in effect far longer than any previous Virginia constitution.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] As a result of the Civil Rights Movement's challenging the restrictions and discrimination practiced against blacks' exercise of constitutional rights, a series of US Supreme Court cases, beginning with *Brown v.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Board of Education* in 1954, the 24th Amendment, and federal legislation: the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and the Voting Rights Act of 1965 had overturned the most controversial aspects of the 1902 Constitution – the provisions restricting voting by African Americans and mandating school segregation.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Combined with the election of Governor Mills Godwin in 1965, there was impetus for governmental change.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Godwin strongly advocated the loosening of the strict constitutional restrictions on state-issued bonds and borrowing and used his power and popularity to push for a new constitution.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] In 1968 a joint resolution of the Virginia General Assembly approved a new commission, chaired by former Governor Albertis Harrison, to revise the constitution.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The Commission on Constitutional Revision presented its report and recommendations to Governor Godwin and the General Assembly in January 1969, and continued to work with them to draft a final consensus version.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The proposed Constitution was overwhelmingly approved by the voters of Virginia (who by then included African American men and women, following passage of federal civil rights legislation in the mid-1960s) and took effect on July 1, 1971.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Since 1971, additional amendments have been passed by the General Assembly and approved by the voters to conform to provisions in the U.S.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Supreme Court and Congressional statute.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The voting age has been reduced to eighteen, voting residency requirements have been removed, and voter registration conforms to the Motor Voter Act.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Additionally, the Virginia Constitution now provides for a General Assembly session following a governor's veto, and the right of the people to hunt, fish and harvest game is guaranteed.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] In 2006, Virginians passed an amendment limiting marriage to "unions between one man and one woman".
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] That has since been overturned by *Obergefell v.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Hodges* (2015), which legalized same-sex marriage throughout the United States.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Article I contains the entire original Virginia Declaration of Rights from the 1776 Constitution.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Several of the sections have been expanded to incorporate concepts from the United States Bill of Rights, including the right to due process, the prohibition against double jeopardy, and the right to bear arms.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Like the Federal Constitution, the Virginia Bill of Rights, in §17, states that the listing of certain rights is not to be construed to exclude other rights held by the people.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] In 1997, a Victims' Rights Amendment was added to the Virginia Bill of Rights as §8-A.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Commonwealth,* the only case so far to interpret this amendment, the Virginia Supreme Court used the Victims's Rights Amendment to support its ruling that an alleged rape victim could not be compelled to submit to a psychiatric evaluation.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] On November 7, 2006, Virginia voters ratified an amendment, previously approved by the General Assembly, prohibiting same-sex marriage, to be added to the Bill of Rights.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The amendment was declared to be in violation the United States Constitution by a U.S.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] District Court Judge on February 13, 2014.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The second Article of the Constitution sets out the procedures and mechanisms for voting, elections and holding office.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Pursuant to Section 1, any Virginia resident over age 18 may vote in state elections; the voting age was reduced from 21 by a 1972 amendment to the federal constitution.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] However, § 1 denies the vote to people who have been determined to be mentally incompetent or anyone convicted of a felony.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Disfranchising convicted felons has been found to be consistent with the Equal Protection Clause of the U.S.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The General Assembly, pursuant to §4, is given wide power to regulate the time, place, and manner of all elections.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] §5 establishes that the only qualifications to hold office in Virginia are that a person must have been a Virginia resident for at least one year and eligible to vote.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Any statute or rule requiring other qualifications is constitutionally invalid under this section.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] But, the General Assembly can impose local residency requirements for election to local governmental bodies or for election to the Assembly in representation of particular districts.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Article III has one section, confirming the principle of separation of powers between the legislative, executive and judicial branches of government.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Unlike the U.S. federal Constitution, the Virginia Constitution explicitly provides that no branch may exercise powers that properly belong to the others.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Separation between the branches of government is also listed as a right of the people in §5 of Article I.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Article IV establishes the basic structure and authority of the Virginia legislature.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The legislative power of the state is vested in the Virginia General Assembly, which consists of the Virginia Senate and the Virginia House of Delegates. §17 of Article IV gives the legislature the power to impeach members of the executive and judicial branches.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The original §14 of Article IV forbade the incorporation of churches, though the Virginia Commission on Constitutional Revision, in its 1969 report, had recognized that the prohibition was probably invalid.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The federal district court for the Western District of Virginia ruled in April 2002 that this provision of the Virginia Constitution was in fact unconstitutional, because it violates the federal constitutional right to the free exercise of religion.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The court found that it is unconstitutional to deny a church the option to incorporate under state law when other groups can incorporate.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The Virginia Constitution was subsequently amended to remove the restriction.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The fifth Article similarly defines the structure and powers of the executive branch.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The Governor of Virginia is invested as the chief executive, though §1 of Article V, provides that the governor may not run for successive terms.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The offices of lieutenant governor and attorney general are established as supporting elected constitutional positions.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The constitutional powers of the governor include the ability to sign legislation, veto bills (which veto may then be overridden by a two-thirds majority of both houses of the assembly), and issue pardons.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Article VI vests judicial power in the Supreme Court of Virginia, along with the subordinate courts created by the General Assembly.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Judges are appointed by a majority vote in the General Assembly to terms of 12 years for Supreme Court Justices and 8 years for other judges.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The Supreme Court, pursuant to §5, has the authority to make rules governing the practice of law and procedures in the courts of the commonwealth (see rules), and the Chief Justice of the Supreme Court is established as the administrative head of the Virginia judicial system.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Article VII of the Constitution sets up the basic framework for the structure and function of local government in Virginia.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Local government may be established at the town (population over 1000), city (population over 5000), county or regional government level.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Article VII gives the General Assembly the power to create general laws for the organization and governing of these political subdivisions, except that regional governments cannot be created without the consent of the majority of the voters who vote on the issue in the region.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Section 4 establishes the constitutional offices of treasurer, sheriff, Commonwealth's Attorney, clerk of court and Commissioner of the Revenue to be elected within each city and county in Virginia.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] A compulsory and free primary and secondary public education for every Virginia child is the focus of Article VIII.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The General Assembly is empowered to determine the funding for the educational system and apportion the cost between state and local government.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] A state Board of Education is established to create school divisions and effectuate the overall educational policies.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Supervision of the individual schools is delegated to local school boards, provided for in §7.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The primary purpose of Article IX is to create the Virginia State Corporation Commission, which is charged with administering the laws that regulate corporations.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The State Corporation Commission also issues charters for Virginia corporations and licenses to do business for "foreign" (non-Virginia) corporations.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Section 5 of Article IX prohibits such foreign corporations from doing anything in Virginia that a Virginia corporation could not do.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Article X establishes the basic structure for taxation of personal property in Virginia.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Pursuant to this Article, all non-exempt real and personal property is subject to taxation at its fair market value.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Section 6 sets out a lengthy list of exempt property, which includes church property, cemeteries, and non-profit school property.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Significant additions to Article X include §7, a budget amendment, which became effective in 1986, and §7-A, which establishes the "Lottery Proceeds Fund", requiring that all proceeds from the lottery be set aside for educational purposes.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Article XI states that it is the general policy of the Commonwealth to preserve, protect and conserve the state's natural and historic resources.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The General Assembly is permitted to further these policies by entering into public-private partnerships or partnerships with federal agencies.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] A 2001 amendment added §4, which establishes hunting and fishing as constitutional rights of Virginians, though the legislature may enact appropriate regulations and restrictions on these rights.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The last Article creates the mechanism for future changes to the Constitution.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Any amendment to the Constitution must first be passed by a majority in each of the two legislative houses.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The proposed amendment must then be held over for consideration by the succeeding elected legislature, where it must again be passed by a majority in each house.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] The amendment then goes on the general ballot and becomes enacted into the Constitution if approved by a majority of the voters.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Alternatively, a two-thirds vote of both Virginia houses may call for the creation of a constitutional convention.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Any revisions or amendments proposed by the constitutional convention are presented to the citizens of Virginia and become law upon approval by a majority of voters.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] There is a perennial discussion over Virginia's unique Constitutional status restricting its governor to one consecutive term, and its method of selecting both trial and appellate judges by state legislature, shared only with South Carolina.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] Since the current constitution was ratified, there have been 53 amendments added to the constitution, concerning issues ranging from tax exemptions and voting rules to budgeting and legislative calendars.
[src:constitution-of-virginia/constitution-of-virginia] In 2020, the state redistricting process was dramatically reshaped, establishing a bipartisan redistricting commission with judicial oversight.
